Assume the template definition is correctly placed in the header. What does this program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
template <typename T>
T doubled(T x) { return x * 2; }
int main() {
    std::cout << doubled(7)   << '\n';
    std::cout << doubled(2.5) << '\n';
}
```

A developer wants to avoid repeating the template definition in every file, so they write:

```cpp
// helper.h
template <typename T>
T halve(T x);

// helper.cpp
#include "helper.h"
template <typename T>
T halve(T x) { return x / 2; }

// main.cpp
#include "helper.h"
#include <iostream>
int main() {
    std::cout << halve(10) << '\n';
}
```

The build fails with a linker error. What is the bug?
